<subSubSection id="C30663EAFFA36C73FCCB45F0A5BAFC54" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA33061FFA36C73FCCB45F0A271FF2B" blockId="21.[811,1457,215,656]" box="[813,1026,215,241]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">SHELL DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA33061FFA36C73FCCB45D0A21EFD4B" blockId="21.[811,1457,215,656]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Medium-sized, robust shells, with relatively low spired whorls. Early spire whorls coeloconoid. Last spire whorls, smooth, straight to concave, creating a low conical to flat outline. Suture impressed. Subsutural flexure shallow, weakly curved, moderately asymmetrical. Shoulder rounded, protruded, creating a bulky outline. Maximum diameter below shoulder. Last whorl straight. Aperture moderate, narrow near suture, straight. Apertural canal wide, fasciole twisted, demarcated from base and inner lip. There are two extreme forms. Form 1 consists of robust forms which are relatively wider in comparison to form 2 and have low angled spire whorls. Form 2 consists of relatively elongated forms with flat spire whorl. Intermediate forms also exist.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA33061FFA36C73FCCB4791A2D4FD15" blockId="21.[813,1457,694,911]" box="[813,1191,694,720]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">DESCRIPTION OF COLOUR PATTERN</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA33061FFA36C73FCCB47F1A5BAFC54" blockId="21.[813,1457,694,911]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">The colour pattern consists of one layer of short and long, fluorescent, spiral dashes, arranged in evenly spaced spiral rows. The spire whorls display wide, fluorescent flammulae, with irregular boundaries on a non-fluorescent base colour. The flammulae do not connect with the colour pattern of the last whorl.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30663EAFFA36C73FCCB4691A24FF8D6" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA33061FFA36C73FCCB4691A5E2FC15" blockId="21.[811,1457,950,1805]" box="[813,913,950,976]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA33061FFA36C73FCCB46F2A2A8FBB4" blockId="21.[811,1457,950,1805]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">
This species shows some variations in the relative diameter of its spire whorls (
<tableCitation id="C69E05DAFFA36C73FC3446D2A26DFBD4" box="[978,1054,1013,1039]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="22.[132,143,1501,1518]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="TABLE 8. — Shell measurements and ratios of Conus (Kalloconus) helladicus n. sp. from the Tortonian of Crete (Greece). Mean and standard deviation are computed from nine specimens, the largest being the holotype (AMPG(IV) 2660)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF6360E9FFA06C70FF6240FAA573F9DE" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" tableUuid="DF6360E9FFA06C70FF6240FAA573F9DE">Table 8</tableCitation>
). The difference between the elongated and robust forms is not very variable. However intermediate forms (
<figureCitation id="13272CE4FFA36C73FC9F4112A585FB94" box="[889,1014,1077,1103]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="22.[132,143,1355,1372]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-311@22.[132,1455,215,1313]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIG. 18. — Conus (Kalloconus) helladicus n. sp. from the Tortonian of Crete (Greece): A, Paratype MNHN.F.A72638: a solid club shaped shell with large relative diameter (form 1) and a distinct colour pattern; B, Holotype AMPG(IV) 2660, Psalidha: a low spired specimen with a relatively narrow diameter (form 2), with a distinct colour pattern; C, Paratype MNHN.F.A72636: a small-sized shell with large relative diameter (form 1); D, Paratype MNHN.F.A72637: a flat spired conid with slightly protruding early spire whorls (form 2). Scale bar: 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5764746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5764746/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Fig. 18B, C</figureCitation>
) between both forms (
<figureCitation id="13272CE4FFA36C73FB0E4112A315FB94" box="[1256,1382,1077,1103]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="22.[132,143,1355,1372]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-311@22.[132,1455,215,1313]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIG. 18. — Conus (Kalloconus) helladicus n. sp. from the Tortonian of Crete (Greece): A, Paratype MNHN.F.A72638: a solid club shaped shell with large relative diameter (form 1) and a distinct colour pattern; B, Holotype AMPG(IV) 2660, Psalidha: a low spired specimen with a relatively narrow diameter (form 2), with a distinct colour pattern; C, Paratype MNHN.F.A72636: a small-sized shell with large relative diameter (form 1); D, Paratype MNHN.F.A72637: a flat spired conid with slightly protruding early spire whorls (form 2). Scale bar: 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5764746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5764746/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Fig. 18A, D</figureCitation>
) point towards the existence of a single species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA33061FFA36C73FCA54152A240FAD4" blockId="21.[811,1457,950,1805]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">
<taxonomicName id="4C1C4BE2FFA36C73FCA54152A2E1FB54" authorityName="Hoernes &amp; Auinger" authorityYear="1879" box="[835,1170,1141,1167]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hungaricus" subGenus="Kalloconus">
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FCA54152A5F5FB54" box="[835,902,1141,1167]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FC7F4152A27FFB54" box="[921,1036,1141,1167]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Kalloconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FBF84152A2E1FB54" box="[1054,1170,1141,1167]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">hungaricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens sensu 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8D4D90FFA36C73FABB4152A5DBFB74" author="LANDAU B. &amp; HARZHAUSER M. &amp; BUYUKMERIC Y. &amp; SILVA C." pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" pagination="1 - 13" refId="ref19741" refString="LANDAU B., HARZHAUSER M., BUYUKMERIC Y. &amp; SILVA C. 2013. - Systematics and palaeobiogeography of the gastropods of the middle Miocene (Serravallian) Karaman Basin of Turkey. Cainozoic Research 1: 1 - 13." type="journal article" year="2013">
Landau 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FCCB41B2A512FB74" box="[813,865,1173,1199]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">et al.</emphasis>
(2013
</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 37, figs 9, 10, pl. 38, fig. 1) from the 
<collectingRegion id="49D8FE83FFA36C73FA9541B2A52EFB14" country="Turkey" name="Karaman" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Karaman</collectingRegion>
Basin (
<collectingCountry id="F30B70F1FFA36C73FC4D4193A589FB14" box="[939,1018,1204,1231]" name="Turkey" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Turkey</collectingCountry>
) are more likely to be 
<taxonomicName id="4C1C4BE2FFA36C73FB004192A5E1FB35" authority="Psarras &amp; Koskeridou &amp; Merle, 2021" authorityName="Psarras &amp; Koskeridou &amp; Merle" authorityYear="2021" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="helladicus" status="n. sp." subGenus="Kalloconus">
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FB004192A354FB14" box="[1254,1319,1205,1231]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FAD14193A3D5FB15" box="[1335,1446,1204,1230]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Kalloconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FCCB41F3A5E1FB35" box="[813,914,1236,1262]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">helladicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25B5108FFA36C73FC7C41F2A5A4FB34" box="[922,983,1237,1263]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, because of their flat spire whorls and their identical colour pattern.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA33061FFA36C73FCA54032A24FF8D6" blockId="21.[811,1457,950,1805]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">
<taxonomicName id="4C1C4BE2FFA36C73FCA54032A3DCFAF4" authority="Hoernes &amp; Auinger, 1879" authorityName="Hoernes &amp; Auinger" authorityYear="1879" box="[835,1455,1300,1327]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hungaricus" subGenus="Kalloconus">
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FCA54032A5F7FAF4" box="[835,900,1301,1327]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FC704033A276FAF5" box="[918,1029,1300,1326]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Kalloconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FBF14033A2F4FAF5" box="[1047,1159,1300,1326]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">hungaricus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF8D4D90FFA36C73FB764032A3DCFAF4" author="HOERNES R. &amp; AUINGER M." box="[1168,1455,1300,1327]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" pagination="1 - 52" refId="ref19161" refString="HOERNES R. &amp; AUINGER M. 1879. - Die Gasteropoden der Meeres- Ablagerungen der ersten und zweiten Miocanen Mediterran-Stufe in der Osterreichisch-Ungarischen Monarchie. Abhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Geologischen Reichsanstalt 12: 1 - 52." type="journal article" year="1879">Hoernes &amp; Auinger, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from Paratethys seems closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1C4BE2FFA36C73FB004012A5E1FAB5" authority="Psarras &amp; Koskeridou &amp; Merle, 2021" authorityName="Psarras &amp; Koskeridou &amp; Merle" authorityYear="2021" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="helladicus" status="n. sp." subGenus="Kalloconus">
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FB004012A354FA94" box="[1254,1319,1333,1359]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FAD14013A3D5FA95" box="[1335,1446,1332,1358]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Kalloconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FCCB4073A5E1FAB5" box="[813,914,1364,1390]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">helladicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25B5108FFA36C73FC714072A5A1FAB4" box="[919,978,1365,1391]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but the medium height, conical spire whorls and the subsutural flexure of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1C4BE2FFA36C73FB884053A3DCFA55" authorityName="Hoernes &amp; Auinger" authorityYear="1879" box="[1134,1455,1396,1423]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hungaricus" subGenus="Kalloconus">
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FB884053A2DCFA55" box="[1134,1199,1396,1422]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FB594053A35DFA55" box="[1215,1326,1396,1422]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Kalloconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FAD94053A3DCFA55" box="[1343,1455,1396,1422]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">hungaricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(medium depth, moderately curved, seeHarzhauser &amp; Landau 2016) are characters separating both species. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1C4BE2FFA36C73FAEC4093A2C8FA35" authority="Hoernes &amp; Auinger, 1879" authorityName="Hoernes &amp; Auinger" authorityYear="1879" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tietzei" subGenus="Kalloconus">
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FAEC4093A338FA15" box="[1290,1355,1460,1486]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FABC4093A523FA35" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Kalloconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FCB940F2A5EEFA35" box="[863,925,1493,1518]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">tietzei</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF8D4D90FFA36C73FC4240F3A2C8FA35" author="HOERNES R. &amp; AUINGER M." box="[932,1211,1492,1518]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" pagination="1 - 52" refId="ref19161" refString="HOERNES R. &amp; AUINGER M. 1879. - Die Gasteropoden der Meeres- Ablagerungen der ersten und zweiten Miocanen Mediterran-Stufe in der Osterreichisch-Ungarischen Monarchie. Abhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Geologischen Reichsanstalt 12: 1 - 52." type="journal article" year="1879">Hoernes &amp; Auinger, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the relatively angulated shoulder and the medium depth of the subsutural flexure (
<bibRefCitation id="EF8D4D90FFA36C73FC6F4334A2B5F9F6" author="HARZHAUSER M. &amp; LANDAU B." box="[905,1222,1555,1582]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" pagination="1" refId="ref18832" refString="HARZHAUSER M. &amp; LANDAU B. 2016. - A revision of the Neogene Conidae and Conorbidae (Gastropoda) of the Paratethys Sea. Zootaxa 4210 (1): 001 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4210.1.1" type="journal article" year="2016">Harzhauser &amp; Landau 2016</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C1C4BE2FFA36C73FB064333A2F2F995" authority="Erunal-Erentoz, 1958" authorityName="Erunal-Erentoz" authorityYear="1958" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="gulemani" subGenus="Kalloconus">
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FB064333A351F9F5" box="[1248,1314,1556,1582]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FAD24334A3D5F9F6" box="[1332,1446,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Kalloconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FCCB4314A5FEF996" box="[813,909,1587,1613]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">gulemani</emphasis>
Erünal-Erentöz, 1958
</taxonomicName>
bears a similar morphology and a colour pattern. The differences between both species exist on the spiral whorl height and the smoother shoulder of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1C4BE2FFA36C73FCAC43B4A209F976" authorityName="Erunal-Erentoz" authorityYear="1958" box="[842,1146,1683,1710]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="gulemani" subGenus="Kalloconus">
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FCAC43B4A5F8F976" box="[842,907,1683,1709]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FC7D43B4A279F976" box="[923,1034,1683,1709]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Kalloconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FBFC43B4A209F976" box="[1050,1146,1683,1709]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">gulemani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. All these species seem to be very closely related, but the differential characters of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1C4BE2FFA36C73FA964394A26AF936" authority="Psarras &amp; Koskeridou &amp; Merle, 2021" authorityName="Psarras &amp; Koskeridou &amp; Merle" authorityYear="2021" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="helladicus" status="n. sp." subGenus="Kalloconus">
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FA964394A3C2F916" box="[1392,1457,1715,1741]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FCD043F4A5D6F936" box="[822,933,1747,1773]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">Kalloconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B968EC73FFA36C73FC5243F4A26AF936" box="[948,1049,1747,1773]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328">helladicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25B5108FFA36C73FBF943F4A22AF936" box="[1055,1113,1747,1773]" pageId="21" pageNumber="1328" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
caused us to consider the Greek material as a new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
